What I see quite often in almost if it's in all the Razor Pages, that we need to specify the model using the `@model`
```html
@page
@model ProductModel
```
for Product.cshtml, and
```html
@page
@model CustomerModel
```
for Customer.cshtml

Can we introduce a new option that allow us to set the model by convention `{PageName}Model` unless we need to use a different name

Consider
```
public class Person
{
    [JsonProperty("Person Name")]
    public string Name { get; set; }
}
```

A patch can be sucessfully applied to this property as 
```C#
var doc = new JsonPatchDocument
{
    Operations = 
    {
        new Operation("add", "/Person Name", null, "New Name"),
    },
};

doc.ApplyTo(person); // This works correctly.
doc.Add("Person Name", "New Name") fails
```

Same deal with back slashes. The invalid char check in that method is kinda unncecessary.

With a page model containing
``` c#
public class IndexModel : PageModel
{
    public IActionResult OnPost()
    {
        return new NotFoundObjectResult($"Executing unsupported handler '{RouteData.Values["handler"]}'.");
    }

    public IActionResult OnPostIntegrals([MinLength(6), Required] int[] ints)
    {
        // ...
        return Page();
    }
}
```
and a page containing
``` html
<form method="post" asp-page-handler="@nameof(IndexModel.OnPostIntegrals)">
    <input type="submit" value="Save nothing" />
</form>
```
Clicking "Save nothing" causes a 404 response, not execution of the named handler method. This feels very much like the oft-complained-about inability to use `<form method="post" controller="@nameof({ControllerClass})">`. (That one mainly has a back-compatibility rationale.)

Suggest we either change page routing to look for a method matching the `handler` route (or query) value (without prepending `On{HTTP Method}`, then falling back to the current method naming) or change the `<form>` tag helper to trim the start of names beginning with `OnGet`, `OnPost` et cetera.

(Found while playing around with #7362.)

For example, a page handler such as
``` c#
public IActionResult OnGet([FromHeader, Required] string hosta)
{
    if (!ModelState.IsValid)
    {
        return BadRequest(ModelState);
    }

    // ...
    return Page();
}
```
should always return a `BadRequestResult` because the `hosta` header doesn't exist. Instead, the `ModelState` is valid and everything proceeds.

Notes: `[Validation]` attributes do work as expected for action parameters. The above problem applies to all `[Validation]` attributes, not just `[Required]`. And, the `[Validation]` attributes are ignored with or without additional attributes; `[FromHeader]` doesn't matter.
